{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/pilonidal-sinus-disease/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"685753f4-4b6f-54e1-b69e-fafd200dee31","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 69295e54-ad2e-4a22-905f-40f70492ea41 --><h1>Pilonidal sinus disease: Summary</h1><!-- end field 69295e54-ad2e-4a22-905f-40f70492ea41 -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 0a1b72d4-06ac-4009-8e5c-30689100b0b7 --><!-- begin field 5d0819d5-2859-468a-bca4-defc5279814a --><ul><li>Pilonidal sinus disease is an inflammatory skin condition that usually occurs in the midline of the natal cleft (although there have been few reported cases involving other parts of the body, such as on the scalp, axilla, groin, and between the fingers).</li><li>Opinions differ as to how it develops; the current consensus is that it is an acquired condition in which loose hairs in the natal cleft are driven into the natal skin, creating a chronic sinus tract which may become infected.</li><li>Risk factors which make pilonidal sinus disease more likely include male gender, age 15–40 years, being white, hirsutism, and obesity.</li><li>Active pilonidal sinus disease can progress to chronic or recurrent disease, and approximately 50% of acute pilonidal abscesses may develop into chronic discharging pilonidal sinus disease despite treatment of the acute abscess.</li><li>Pilonidal sinus disease often recurs after surgical treatment, and the recurrence rate depends on the specific surgical method used. For example, simple incision and drainage is associated with an estimated 15–40% recurrence rate.</li><li>Complications of pilonidal sinus disease include cellulitis, sepsis, chronic pain, and altered body image and self-esteem.</li><li>The diagnosis of pilonidal sinus disease can usually be made on history and examination alone. On examination, people with the disease will almost always have characteristic midline pits in the natal cleft. </li><li>Investigations may be considered if there is doubt about the diagnosis or to exclude differential diagnoses, such as Crohn’s disease and infectious processes (such as tuberculosis and syphilis). </li><li>For people with asymptomatic pilonidal sinus disease, management includes:<ul><li>A watch and wait approach, with reassurance that treatment is not necessary.</li><li>Giving advice on meticulous perianal hygiene.</li></ul></li><li>For people with acute pilonidal abscess, management includes:<ul><li>Urgent same-day incision and drainage by a colorectal or general surgeon, for most people.</li><li>Offering analgesia for pain and/or fever.</li><li>Considering treatment with antibiotics if cellulitis is suspected.</li><li>Giving advice on long-term measures that may reduce the risk of recurrence, such as meticulous perianal hygiene and buttock hair removal techniques.</li></ul></li><li>For people with discharging pilonidal sinus disease, management includes:<ul><li>Referral to a colorectal or general surgical unit for consideration for surgical excision, the urgency depending on clinical judgement.</li><li>Offering analgesia for pain and/or fever.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 5d0819d5-2859-468a-bca4-defc5279814a --><!-- end item 0a1b72d4-06ac-4009-8e5c-30689100b0b7 -->","topic":{"id":"c75a0f03-60df-5718-b4ad-d6e32f354f69","topicId":"f6f74445-1669-4cf9-9d42-9881d6be83d1","topicName":"Pilonidal sinus disease","slug":"pilonidal-sinus-disease","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"685753f4-4b6f-54e1-b69e-fafd200dee31","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5f89fe48-e69a-565c-9208-1e39eafec872","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e102bb7d-89e7-571b-bb6b-e35165528fd8","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"026c97f4-f023-5833-9e34-1248e8d6f2a4","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"